 sits at neutral \u2014 a reflection of a market that has done a reasonable job of reclaiming lost ground but has yet to convincingly break above the prior high.\n\nThe structure story is one of compression. After the 2 July sell-off, which carved out a low just above the 160.60 prior reaction zone \u2014 a level that has now registered four distinct touches \u2014 price spent the better part of a fortnight grinding back toward the 162.60\u2013162.85 resistance cluster. Each daily candle in that recovery phase has been relatively contained, with upper wicks appearing on several sessions, suggesting sellers have been active on approaches to the highs. The 160.60 zone remains the key structural support to watch; a clean daily close beneath it would bring the 159.87 and 159.61 prior reaction zones into focus as the next meaningful areas of potential demand. None of the identified zones sit on the resistance side, which underscores that the upper boundary of this range is defined by recent price action rather than a formally mapped level.\n\nOn the H1 chart, today's session has been characterised by a gradual drift lower from the 162.42 intraday high printed during the European afternoon. Price slipped through the 162.20 area \u2014 which had provided a degree of intraday support through much of the morning \u2014 and by the early Asian hours had edged down toward 161.90. The hourly structure shows a sequence of lower highs since the 20:00 peak, and the pair is now testing the lower end of the day's range. There is no obvious H1 support until the 161.50\u2013161.60 area, which corresponds to prior consolidation from mid-July.\n\nThe calendar is empty for today, which removes an obvious catalyst for a directional break. Absent data, the pair is likely to remain subject to positioning flows and any broader risk sentiment shifts. Thin calendar days in USD/JPY can occasionally produce exaggerated moves if Japanese officials comment on yen levels, so that remains a background consideration.\n\nThe bullish read would be challenged on a sustained move back beneath 160.60 on the daily close, which would suggest the recovery from the July low has stalled and that the broader range is shifting lower. Conversely, a clean break and hold above 162.85 would reopen the question of whether the pair has scope to extend the broader uptrend. For now, neither scenario has been confirmed.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}